article.description: Behind another great point-guard performance, Georgia Tech outlasted Kansas in OT.
article.headline: Jack's 29 pace Jackets past Jayhawks
article.linkText: Jack-ed up: Tech follows point back to Final Four

inlines.body:
Dick Vitale's Tourney Take
What a gutty performance by Georgia Tech coach Paul Hewitt's club. Tech did something few teams could do as it made it to the winner's circle without its top scorer for most of the game. B.J. Elder's ankle kept him on the sideline for most of the game, and losing a prolific scorer was a tough task against a talented Kansas team.

The Yellow Jackets would not lose because super soph Jarrett Jack made sure of it. Jack attacked the basket right from the start. He was aggressive on the offensive end with his penetration and took the game in his hands while his buddy Elder sat on the sidelines.
More on Sunday's Games

article.story: LAWRENCE, Kan. (AP) -- Wayne Simien had 13 points and 15 rebounds to lead No. 1 Kansas over Washburn 79-70 in an exhibition game Sunday night. Washburn trailed by as many as 13 points in the second half, but Randy Brown made a 3-pointer to cut the deficit to 73-66. After Christian Moody made a free throw for Kansas, Brown missed a 3-pointer and Simien hit a jumper to give the Jayhawks a 10-point lead with 2 minutes left. Kansas led 57-51 when Russell Robinson hit a layup and a 3-pointer on consecutive possessions. Moody added four more points in a 12-5 run. Keith Langford scored 11 points for the Jayhawks. Miles, Moody, and J.R. Giddens each had 10 points. Washburn was led by Travis Robbins' 14 points and six rebounds. Karlton Mims and Carl Jenkins added 12 points for the Ichabods. Simien was held scoreless for the first 14 minutes of the game. His first basket broke a 26-all tie and started a run that gave Kansas a 39-30 lead en route to a 42-37 halftime advantage. The 3-point line was extended to 20 feet, 6 inches, and the free-throw lane was extended 1½ feet on either side in an experiment by the NCAA's rules committee. The changes can be implemented during any exhibition game before January 1, 2005, and include a 2 feet arc underneath the hoop as a charging and blocking restriction area. Kansas went 6-0 in exhibition play, including a four-game series in Canada over Labor Day weekend. The Jayhawks open the regular season on Friday against Vermont. Washburn was 0-2 in exhibition games, also losing to Purdue 81-72 last week.
